Still Light Years Ahead? - Is the Golden State Warriors' Dynasty Over?

CMSC320 Final Tutorial | by Shreyes Varde

Motivation

Bill Russell's Celtics. Magic and Bird in the 80s. Jordan's Bulls. The Shaq and Kobe Lakers. The Duncan Spurs, the Heatles. NBA history has been defined by dynasties, and in 2014-15, a new team burst onto the scene, ready to take the mantle. Led by a 6'3'' guard from Davidson College and surrounded by perfect complementary players and an unparalleled coaching staff, the Golden State Warriors set the all-time record for wins in a season and won a championship. Then in the summer of 2016, they added Kevin Durant in free agency, widely considered a top 3 player in the league. They then proceeded to dominate the rest of the league from 2017-2019, winning back-to-back championships, making the finals all three years.

Yet 2019 was a far cry from the success that the Warriors had enjoyed for the past half-decade. Durant left to another team, and Stephen Curry and Klay Thompson suffered season-ending injuries. In 2020, Curry returned, but his individual brilliance was not enough to lift a mediocre roster and they missed the playoffs. It seemed as if the Warriors' run was over, and many talking heads on TV belabored this point.

However, the Warriors were not done yet. In 2022, they came back with a vengeance, starting 18-2 in their first 20 games. Injuries to key players hurt them along the way, but they entered the playoffs as the 3rd seed in the West, eventually making it to the NBA Finals where they beat the Boston Celtics in 6 games. This made the overall count now 4 finals in 8 years, not to mention 6 total appearances. It was clear this was the next dynasty of NBA history, one up there with the very best.

Yet the past two years have not been kind to the Warriors. In 2022-23, they lost in the second round of the playoffs after a hard fought win in 7 games over the upstart Sacramento Kings. In 2023-24, they didn't even make the playoffs, losing to those very Kings in the play-in games. With the core players getting older and the league getting more competitive, much has been said about this being the end of the Warriors dynasty.

  • Article by CBS Sports (here)
  • Article by The Athletic (here)
  • Article by The Mercury News (here)

But is is really the end? And if it is, how can the Warriors get back to their glory days? To investigate this, I took a data-driven approach towards analyzing three different causes:

  • Has Stephen Curry declined?
  • Is the support from the complementary players not as strong?
  • Is Coach Steve Kerr still at the top of his game?

My objective is to use data, modeling, and statistics to see if any of these reasons have significant statistical backing, and we hope you (the reader) are able to learn more about analyzing data through Python, proving or disproving claims using statistics, while also gaining a better understanding of how data science can be applied to contexts such as basketball and sports.

Dataset 2

However, while Stephen Curry is the engine of the Warriors dynasty, we also need to analyze the players around him. The rosters for the past 10 seasons are available, once again, on Basketball Reference. It is important to note that the rosters are organized by highest-minute players to lowest-minute. A starting lineup in the NBA is made up of 5 players, so for our purposes, we are going to look at the 5 players who played the most minutes every year for the Warriors. This should give us a good idea as to the pieces around Stephen Curry.

In[6]:
# create formatted string which we can later input year into
base_csv = "rosters/{}.csv"

others = pd.DataFrame()

# list of years for which we are looking at the rosters for
# note, excluded 2020 because Stephen Curry was injured, so not a good setup for seeing if he has help
years = [2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2021, 2022, 2023, 2024]

for year in years:
    # add year into file path so it can be read into csv
    csv_file = base_csv.format(year)
    df = pd.read_csv(csv_file)

    # add column of year so easier to differentiate between players
    df['year'] = year

    # only want the top 5 highest minute players and continually concatenate onto larger dataframe
    others = pd.concat([others, df[:5]])

# Stephen Curry is one of the 5 highest-minute players but we already have his data, so let's filter him out of this dataset.
others = others[others['Player'] != "Stephen Curry"]
others

Dataset 3

Finally, if we're looking at the players, it's only fair we analyze the coaching too. Steve Kerr is a championship-winning coach, but how much of that is due to his system versus the players he has at his disposal? To test this, I took data from his entire (still running) tenure as coach of the Warriors as well as the year before (2013-14), when Mark Jackson was coach. I included this first year to see if there's any sizable jumps that we can see as a result of the transition in coaches. The data I took is regarding the offensive and defensive rating of the team, because coaches have a large hand in that, whether it's defining a set scheme, drawing up plays to execute, making adjustments, and getting players to buy in to the system.

Graph 4: Taking a Look at Curry's Advanced Stats

There are a lot of advanced stats we can look at, but for this specific graph, we will be analyzing Curry's Value Over Replacement Player (VORP). If you would like to dive deep into the math behind the stat, you can follow this link, but I will explain the basics here. VORP basically measures how good a player is relative to a "replacement player" with a baseline score of 0. It uses other metrics like Box Plus-Minus (BPM) to capture in one metric how much better a player is relative to competition. The higher a player's VORP, the more valuable they are compared to a baseline role-player.

To give a sense of scale, a VORP of +4.0 is an All-Star season, +6.0 is All-NBA, +8.0 is a peak MVP season, and +10.0 is an all-time historic season.

# function that aggregates the total points across the 4 other players based on year
def total_ppg_for_year(df, year):
    total = df[df['year'] == year]['PTS'].sum()
    return total

combined_ppg_of_others = pd.DataFrame()

years = [2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2021, 2022, 2023, 2024]

# create empty list to append total pts based on year to
total_ppg = []

combined_ppg_of_others['Year'] = years

for year in years:
    # calls function and appends result to list
    total_ppg.append(total_ppg_for_year(others, year))

# make updated list a column in df

Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML

Hypothesis Test 1: Does Stephen Curry's scoring output have an effect on wins?

Considering that Stephen Curry is the engine of the Warriors dynasty, it would logically follow that his performance has an impact on how the team does overall. Let's test this with a hypothesis test.

Here are the null and alternate hypotheses:

H0: There is no relationship between Stephen Curry's Points per Game (PPG) and the number of wins.

H1: There is a relationship between Stephen Curry's Points per Game (PPG) and the number of wins.

First, let's add a column of wins to the dataframe.

ML Model 1 (Multivariate Regression): Modeling Stephen Curry's Effect on Wins

Below, we will store our features in X and our target in y. We will use scikit-learn's train_test_split to randomly split the data into 90-10 training and testing data. This is because we have a small data set; ideally, your testing set would be bigger.

Looking at the tree, we see that even with just one independent variable, it is overly complex and deep. This might lead to overfitting -- is that what's happening here?

In[44]:
model_dtree.score(X_train, y_train)
Out[44]:
1.0

Aha! From this, we see that the r-squared value is perfect, meaning the decision tree is perfectly predicting our training data, which means it's overfitting. This could be the reason why it's doing so bad on the test data in turn. We can fix this by tuning the parameters of the decision tree. I limited the max_depth of the tree so it doesn't get too deep and I also made sure each leaf has a specific number of samples. Let's see how our model changes.

In[45]:
model_d_tree2 = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=50, max_depth=3, min_samples_leaf=2)

Next Steps + Insight Learned

At the end of writing this notebook, I was surprised at some of my own findings. For one, I thought that the supporting pieces would have a larger impact, but at least from this analysis, it is clear that the key drivers of the Warriors dynasty are the star and the coach, and if the team wants to get back to its previous glory, those two will have to remain at peak level.

However, that doesn't mean that the general manager of the Warriors (Mike Dunleavy Jr.) can afford to strike out on the margins. We saw in this notebook how the support around Stephen Curry drastically dropped off this year, and we also saw how Curry, while still great, is not at peak MVP levels anymore. Thus, to support him, the rest of the roster will have to be rounded out even better.

Through an extension of this project, there are some questions I'd like to explore further. I'd like to model how the team would have done if Kevin Durant had not joined in 2016. Would they still have enjoyed the same level of success? I also wanted to look at Steve Kerr's work more closely. On-court schemes are just one part of a coach's job. Prudently calling timeouts, success of set plays, even managing relationships off the court, these are all things that, off the eye test, Steve Kerr excels at, and I'd love to find the data to either back it up or prove my intuition wrong.

Regardless of whether the dynasty is over or not, I learned a lot while doing this project. I've been a basketball fan since I was five years old, and even though I marveled at athletic freaks like Kobe Bryant or Lebron James, Stephen Curry and his Warriors were the first team to really make me fall in love with the game. As a fan, I think they still have one more run in them, and now, I have the data and analysis to back up my homerism!
